Microscopic mechanism

• When a bond breaks in shear, a new 
bond will usually form immediately 
afterwards between the new atomic 
neighbors. This process of bond 
breaking and reformation controls 
defect nucleation.

• The stress needed to cause such an 
event should correspond to the 
theoretical shear strength we 
calculated in class.

• A defect should nucleate when this 
stress is reached to relieve the high 
strain energy built up at this point

